    {
      "id": "E1i67UQTXnPqKmOfDbZVR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1841.2522319465234,
      "y": 3153.817736111383,
      "width": 737.51953125,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b17",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 895437218,
      "version": 316,
      "versionNonce": 166478206,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775679990849,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "6M drivers\n3M active in any given time\n3M * 5 -> 600k Transaction Per Second (TPS) -> That's a lot of updates.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "6M drivers\n3M active in any given time\n3M * 5 -> 600k Transaction Per Second (TPS) -> That's a lot of updates.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "B4XYWzVxyYEEaYaXvNYPK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2779.2636937532916,
      "y": 2767.4762476119067,
      "width": 1989.958740234375,
      "height": 1000,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b18",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 799406114,
      "version": 3399,
      "versionNonce": 1076060606,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775679990849,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Case1: Postgress DB\n    -- We can store lat/long in colums and then let's say we search it based on rider's location.\n    Sucks:\n        -- Postgress uses Btree from indexing -> which is optimised for 1D scanning not 2D with lat & long\n        -- Queries will suck, slow transactions and lagging.\n        -- Most of all -> there would be a lot of rows to scans.\n        -- Postgress can handle 2-3k TPS at max with replicas and optimised hardware.\n    \n    BAD CHOICE !!\n\n    Possible sol for above:\n        -- We need to optimise the lookup this search -> \"Geo-Spatial Index\" [Makes Querying geo data faster] -> Go with a Quard Tree [Postgress has extension as PostGIS ]\n            -- Quard Trees:\n                -> They take a map -> they recursively keeps on dividing it into quadrants, smaller and smaller.\n                -> there is a k value -> thats like it will keep on dividing till it reaches that limit.\n                -> Kind of divide till you reduce it to k elements present in a particular region i.e till you get those leaf nodes while keep on branching the tree.\n            -- issue:\n                -> New location added -> we need to re-index the quard tree to find new leaf nodes again -> that's a computation headache !\n                \n        -- This high TPS req we need to reduce it to may be 4k or so -> Well add a queue before the location DB -> it will queue the incoming req and process it async way.\n            -> issues:\n                1. Well the batching that high TPS -> introduce good amount of Latency in location updates.\n\n        \n        \"Quard- Tree\" is good when we have uneven density of the nodes eg: you searching campsites in a country, lot of nodes but in ocean few nodes. Also No high TPS [ Re-indexing the tree is costly ]\n            \n\n\nCase2: Redis \n    -- An in-memory datastore can handle high TPS. [100k to 1M TPS if optimised well ] -> we have a redis cluster.\n    -- For Quering Geo-spatial Index:\n        - Redis supports \"Geo-hashing\"  -> Map Region into 4 quadrants -> Recursively keeps on breaking each quadrants into 4 again and again -> untill we have what we need.\n        - Endsup with a base32 Encoded string eg: \"u4pruydaavj\"  --> longer the string more precise and accurate the location is.  [Fucking amazing !! ]\n        - also chars from left to right -> it zooms in like first 4 can tell you about the region, next would tell the country, then next would be city and so on....\n        Advantages:\n              1. Cheap and easy to calculate a geo-hash  2. Easy to store  3. It dosnot need any DS like quard-Tree.\n\n    \n       \"Geo Hashing\" best for Proximity based queries for location, Supports out of the box from Redis\n        ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Case1: Postgress DB\n    -- We can store lat/long in colums and then let's say we search it based on rider's location.\n    Sucks:\n        -- Postgress uses Btree from indexing -> which is optimised for 1D scanning not 2D with lat & long\n        -- Queries will suck, slow transactions and lagging.\n        -- Most of all -> there would be a lot of rows to scans.\n        -- Postgress can handle 2-3k TPS at max with replicas and optimised hardware.\n    \n    BAD CHOICE !!\n\n    Possible sol for above:\n        -- We need to optimise the lookup this search -> \"Geo-Spatial Index\" [Makes Querying geo data faster] -> Go with a Quard Tree [Postgress has extension as PostGIS ]\n            -- Quard Trees:\n                -> They take a map -> they recursively keeps on dividing it into quadrants, smaller and smaller.\n                -> there is a k value -> thats like it will keep on dividing till it reaches that limit.\n                -> Kind of divide till you reduce it to k elements present in a particular region i.e till you get those leaf nodes while keep on branching the tree.\n            -- issue:\n                -> New location added -> we need to re-index the quard tree to find new leaf nodes again -> that's a computation headache !\n                \n        -- This high TPS req we need to reduce it to may be 4k or so -> Well add a queue before the location DB -> it will queue the incoming req and process it async way.\n            -> issues:\n                1. Well the batching that high TPS -> introduce good amount of Latency in location updates.\n\n        \n        \"Quard- Tree\" is good when we have uneven density of the nodes eg: you searching campsites in a country, lot of nodes but in ocean few nodes. Also No high TPS [ Re-indexing the tree is costly ]\n            \n\n\nCase2: Redis \n    -- An in-memory datastore can handle high TPS. [100k to 1M TPS if optimised well ] -> we have a redis cluster.\n    -- For Quering Geo-spatial Index:\n        - Redis supports \"Geo-hashing\"  -> Map Region into 4 quadrants -> Recursively keeps on breaking each quadrants into 4 again and again -> untill we have what we need.\n        - Endsup with a base32 Encoded string eg: \"u4pruydaavj\"  --> longer the string more precise and accurate the location is.  [Fucking amazing !! ]\n        - also chars from left to right -> it zooms in like first 4 can tell you about the region, next would tell the country, then next would be city and so on....\n        Advantages:\n              1. Cheap and easy to calculate a geo-hash  2. Easy to store  3. It dosnot need any DS like quard-Tree.\n\n    \n       \"Geo Hashing\" best for Proximity based queries for location, Supports out of the box from Redis\n        ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gvPn3pbLLgSUj80ZFr0im",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1759.4135520898521,
      "y": 3314.9083788398248,
      "width": 827.9395751953125,
      "height": 200,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b19",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 533038690,
      "version": 726,
      "versionNonce": 453802494,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775679990849,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Can we reduce this high TPS ? \n    1. Well we can have some Product trade-offs -> update location in 1 min.\n    2. Adaptive updates in client itself !\n        -- status of drivers -> accepting ride or not ?\n        -- Speed -> is vehicle parked -> No need to update same location.\n        -- proximity to rider location.\n\n--> This should reduce 600k to some 100-200k !  [ Minor Trade-offs do help, huh !]",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Can we reduce this high TPS ? \n    1. Well we can have some Product trade-offs -> update location in 1 min.\n    2. Adaptive updates in client itself !\n        -- status of drivers -> accepting ride or not ?\n        -- Speed -> is vehicle parked -> No need to update same location.\n        -- proximity to rider location.\n\n--> This should reduce 600k to some 100-200k !  [ Minor Trade-offs do help, huh !]",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "xyd4Jkm0DzrT66KDCH0_k",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 636.9419578268598,
      "y": 3356.528369254588,
      "width": 2012.278564453125,
      "height": 975,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1A",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1976005538,
      "version": 2779,
      "versionNonce": 1394169890,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775680058604,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Consistency matching:\n    \n1. We don't send more then 1 req at a time for a given ride\n    - Can be logic in the Ride Matching Microservice.\n    - So we have let's say list of 10 top drivers -> eligible for ride.\n    - Send req to a driver -> wait for 10s -> if not responded -> move to the next guy !\n\n\n2. We don't send any driver more than 1 req at a time.\n    - This is tricky ! \n    - So in case of horizontal scaled system -> multiple instance of Ride matching microservie is up.\n    - Somehow we need to track -> which driver we have requested so that it doesn't clash with same req from different instance of the same service !\n    - Sol:\n         -- add a status field in driver Entity -> when we send a req to driver -> update this status to \"Requested\".\n         -- next if any one requesting this driver -> First check if he is available or not ?\n      Issues:\n         -- This approach is okay ! but we want the driver to accept/decline in 5 sec so, doesnot really make sense in adding a status field.\n         --  In above sol, if the driver don;t perfrom any action, he is stuck with a stale state that prevents him for getting any other ride !\n        Sol: \n            \"Distribured lock with Redis\"\n            -- \"Redis Cluster\"  -> Comes with build-in TTL out of the box.\n            --  So we can set driverId set to \"True\" with a TTL of 5 sec.  --> So for 5 sec that driverId is not locaked after 5sec, it automatically removed.\n            -- So now any instance trying to request a driver --> first check in the distributed lock  [ Fast since Hash-Map ] -> If present it ignores -> If not then add a entry there and send a notification.\n            -- A driver doesnot reply -> TTL will remove it from the lock.\n\n        case2: Use the Primary DB as Dynamo DB\n            -- In Dynamo DB we can have a seperate table saying Driver Lock  -> takes DriverId  and set TTLs in it.\n\n        \n            \nIn the Ride Matching Service:\n            \n            while (noMatch) {\n                driver = nextDriver\n                lock(driver)\n                sendNotification(driver)\n                wait(10s)\n            }\n            ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Consistency matching:\n    \n1. We don't send more then 1 req at a time for a given ride\n    - Can be logic in the Ride Matching Microservice.\n    - So we have let's say list of 10 top drivers -> eligible for ride.\n    - Send req to a driver -> wait for 10s -> if not responded -> move to the next guy !\n\n\n2. We don't send any driver more than 1 req at a time.\n    - This is tricky ! \n    - So in case of horizontal scaled system -> multiple instance of Ride matching microservie is up.\n    - Somehow we need to track -> which driver we have requested so that it doesn't clash with same req from different instance of the same service !\n    - Sol:\n         -- add a status field in driver Entity -> when we send a req to driver -> update this status to \"Requested\".\n         -- next if any one requesting this driver -> First check if he is available or not ?\n      Issues:\n         -- This approach is okay ! but we want the driver to accept/decline in 5 sec so, doesnot really make sense in adding a status field.\n         --  In above sol, if the driver don;t perfrom any action, he is stuck with a stale state that prevents him for getting any other ride !\n        Sol: \n            \"Distribured lock with Redis\"\n            -- \"Redis Cluster\"  -> Comes with build-in TTL out of the box.\n            --  So we can set driverId set to \"True\" with a TTL of 5 sec.  --> So for 5 sec that driverId is not locaked after 5sec, it automatically removed.\n            -- So now any instance trying to request a driver --> first check in the distributed lock  [ Fast since Hash-Map ] -> If present it ignores -> If not then add a entry there and send a notification.\n            -- A driver doesnot reply -> TTL will remove it from the lock.\n\n        case2: Use the Primary DB as Dynamo DB\n            -- In Dynamo DB we can have a seperate table saying Driver Lock  -> takes DriverId  and set TTLs in it.\n\n        \n            \nIn the Ride Matching Service:\n            \n            while (noMatch) {\n                driver = nextDriver\n                lock(driver)\n                sendNotification(driver)\n                wait(10s)\n            }\n            ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
